Penguins Love RMarkdown

Carina

November 03, 2020

The YAML header in the .Rmd file specifies how your document will be outputted. I like to use html so that I can have a floating table of contents, and if you want to be able to caption figures and reference them in the text and/or if you want numbered sections then use bookdown::html_document2.

Theres an invisible setup chunk here where I specify global options for all chunks going forward. If Im making analysis reports to share Ill usually set echo = FALSE so that my code isnt cluttering up the document, and for chunks where neither the code nor the output needs to be shown Ill set include = FALSE in those individual chunk options.

For this doc though, Ill leave echo = TRUE so you can see both the code and the output.

1 Set up

Load packages first. Ive named the below chunk packages (even though you cant see that name in the output html file) to make it easier to refer to when Im editing the .Rmd file.

# install.packages("palmerpenguins")
library(palmerpenguins)
library(magrittr)
library(tidyverse)

The magrittr package is super handy for the %<>% pipe. Notice how I can put text in backticks to make them look like code in the output document.

2 Do male and female penguins have different bill lengths?

We can do a t-test to answer this question.

results = t.test(bill_length_mm ~ sex, data = penguins) %>% 
  print()
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  bill_length_mm by sex
## t = -6.6725, df = 329.29, p-value = 1.066e-10
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -4.865676 -2.649908
## sample estimates:
## mean in group female   mean in group male 
##             42.09697             45.85476

Ive saved the results as the variable results so that I can use them when writing up a results section:

There is a statistically significant difference between male and female penguins bill lengths, t(329.29) = -6.67, p < .001.

To add in-line R code (as opposed to code in chunks), place the code in backticks and put r at the start of your code.

2.1 Plot the results

penguins %>% 
  drop_na() %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = sex, y = bill_length_mm, colour = sex, fill = sex)) +
  geom_violin(alpha = .4) +
  geom_jitter(alpha = .6) +
  scale_colour_manual(values = c("slateblue1", "tan1")) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("slateblue1", "tan1")) +
  guides(colour = FALSE, fill = FALSE) +
  stat_summary(fun = mean, geom = "point", colour = "black") +
  stat_summary(fun.data = mean_se, geom = "errorbar", width = .1, colour = "black") +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(x = "Sex", y = "Bill length (mm)") +
  scale_x_discrete(labels = c("female" = "Female", "male" = "Male"))

Figure 2.1: Difference in bill length between male and female penguins

Figure 2.1 indicates that female penguins have shorter bills than do males.

To be able to refer to the figure, the code chunk containing the figure code needs to have both a name and a caption.
